##The Chinese in the epidemic area of Taegu: Some people stay, some people flee

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

The following article is from the Earth's youth map, the author of green

The alternative to being young

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After dinner, old Cao went to the balcony to smoke as usual. After smoking, he suddenly walked quickly to the kitchen, to his daughter, who was washing the dishes, he said, "I was looking at it from the balcony. Look at the beautiful night scene in Taegu. It doesn't look like a virus at all. Am I dreaming? Pinch me hard. I must be dreaming. "

"It doesn't hurt, I must be dreaming, " he said, laughing as his daughter squeezed his stomach with all her might.

Until early March, he was reluctant to acknowledge that Taegu had been hit hard. A total of 7,513 cases have been confirmed nationwide, including 5,663 in Daegu, South Korea's central epidemic prevention department said Monday, Yonhap reported. Arguably, Taegu is to South Korea what Wuhan is to China.

Every Spring Equinox, Daegu's cherry blossoms will usher in the most beautiful moment. The country's fourth-largest city after Seoul, Busan and Incheon, with a population of 2.6 m, is surrounded by mountains in a mountainous basin on the Geumho River River, a tributary of Nakdong River's middle reaches.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
View of Taegu by MOCO

He comes from a Koreans family in Jilin Province, and Daegu was their first stop when he and his wife moved to South Korea in 2007. Old Cao's daughter, who goes to school in Changchun, Jilin Province, comes to live with her parents every winter and summer vacation, and Daegu has become the family's second home. On January 11, she flew from her hometown to visit her parents in Taegu, the 18th time she has flown to South Korea. The family, who had not seen each other for nearly six months, planned to spend the New Year together and then take advantage of the holiday to visit Seoul and Jeju Island.

Equally fond of the city is Albert, who has lived in Taegu for 10 years. From her undergraduate degree to her phd, Daegu has witnessed her life. For Bai, Taegu was a "just right" city, with just the right density, consumption level and facilities, not crowded or rushed. The only thing that's not quite right is the extreme summer temperatures. Taegu is a sub-tropical monsoon climate city with a "40 degree summer" like Wuhan, known locally as the "furnace" . A Bai is from Inner Mongolia. The climate of Daegu basin is quite different from that of his hometown, but a Bai likes Daegu very much. "The atmosphere of the whole North Gyeongsang Province is as warm as the 40-degree summer here. ".

Like the Cherry Blossoms at Keimyung University, one of the 10 most beautiful campuses in South Korea, the blossoms are overgrown with trees and clouds. Every spring, it is a good place for local people to enjoy the cherry blossoms.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Keimyung University in full bloom. Photograph: Albai

This year, however, the Cao family's long planned outing fell through, and the Keimyung University campus has been closed to outsiders. The Cherry blossoms are about to bloom in Taegu, but not many people care.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taegu Street. By Albert

Taegu is a city of nightlife, and cafes are still packed at 1 am or 2 am. At first, Cao only heard about the new pneumonia on the news. The first case of new pneumonia was found in South Korea on January 20. No more than four new cases have been confirmed daily since then, and most of the patients have a history of travel abroad or are close contacts. Since there was no significant increase in the number of confirmed cases, one case was immediately isolated for treatment, information was readily available and there were no severe cases or deaths, and there were not many people wearing masks on the streets of Korea at that time.

A 61-year-old woman with the code name "31" in Daegu, South Korea, was diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia on February 18. The patient was treated at a hospital in Daegu on February 6 after a traffic accident, discharged on the 17th. During this period, she twice to the new heaven and Earth Church to attend church, but also on the 15th with friends to a hotel in Daegu dinner. According to preliminary statistics, more than 1,000 people attended the two services. On February 20, the South Korean "joongang Ilbo" reported that many of the new cases were related to the new World Church in Damingdong, south district of Daegu city, where the confirmed patient No. 31 frequented.

After the emergence of this "super-spreader" , the number of infected people in South Korea began to double, people are gradually aware that the situation is not the same. The most obvious change is that more people are wearing masks on the streets. People began to snap up supplies, and the price of a mask rose from 2,000 won to 6,000 won.

South Korea Central Epidemic Prevention Countermeasures Headquarters on the afternoon of March 6, because the outbreak intensified, the South Korean market "shortage of masks" increasingly serious, from the 6th to implement restrictions on the purchase of masks measures. Under the measure, South Koreans will be allowed to buy up to two masks each during the week. Starting from the 9th, South Koreans will be restricted to buying mask products according to the odd and even numbers of the Year of birth: People born in odd years will be allowed to buy masks only on odd days; People born in even-numbered years can only buy face masks on even-numbered days. Each person is limited to 2 face masks per week.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taegu Street. By Albert

Although hospitals in Taegu are in a state of emergency, there are shortages of supplies, medical staff and beds. But Daegu city public transport is still not suspended, old Cao is still normal to work, the company according to the number of working days issued masks, the community also issued to each mask. The performance of his wife's Club has declined markedly, but there is still no sign of stopping work. Daughter at home online class for learning, she teased this special period most suitable for weight loss, "the door and can not go out, no food surplus at home. ".

Relatively speaking, the arrival of a white epidemic is prepared. On New Year's Eve, she was discussing the epidemic with her friends who were overseas students. After realizing the seriousness of the epidemic, she arranged to go to the supermarket and drug store the next day to stock up on face masks, disinfectant and other anti-epidemic materials. At the time, Chinese students were buying face masks at the pharmacy, and almost everyone had a stack of them. "At that time, Koreans were not very conscious. Those wearing masks on the street must have been Chinese students studying abroad. ".

Bai was once treated as an alien on the subway because he wore a mask to communicate with his friends in Chinese, and was given an unfriendly look. On January 23, South Koreans launched a petition on their Blue House home page asking the government to ban Chinese people from entering the country; some restaurants even posted the words "no Chinese allowed" directly on their doors. At that time, both Chinese and Koreans felt that pneumonia in South Korea could be prevented and controlled and would not spread widely.

But no one expected such a sudden outbreak in Taegu. Tung Shan Hospital, a Keimyung University affiliated hospital, was set up to treat fever patients in Taegu. The hospital, which was in close contact with the virus, was only 200 metres away from the school. The House she rented was just a block from the school, and the small room was filled with books. She lived with her cat.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Albert is a volunteer in the temporary quarantine station of our school. PHOTOGRAPHER: Albert

Since the outbreak, the Keimyung University has been emphasizing the prevention of the new coronavirus to students and asked them to return to school from February 21 to 24. It was her first time wearing protective clothing, goggles, the first time wearing a surgical mask, she felt "especially hard, wearing a few hours after the face red hot, out of breath. ".

Although Daegu has been a disaster area, but Bai did not feel that life has changed significantly. The courses to be taken in the last semester have basically been taken, the rest is the graduation thesis. She has been comforting friends to maintain an optimistic attitude, "as long as we stick to the door, I believe we can adhere to the past to win. ".

What really made her feel like she was at the center of the storm were the media interviews and the vlog shoot requests. She filmed the deserted streets and their isolation life, interview the owner of the Malatang shop, whose turnover was reduced by 90% due to the epidemic, complained about the price of 50 yuan two pears... one day she was not in a good condition, and had a Migraine, insomnia and acne on her face, she ordered a 1,000-milliliter coffee to go and "fed her tension with her favorite Latte" . Although there were many people who cared about her, she was unavoidably disturbed by the realization that she was at the center of the storm.

In a chat, a local resident in Taegu discussed his views on the outbreak with Xiaoxue, who spoke less than fluent Chinese, "I'm worried because there are more and more patients. China is a communist country and can control people, but South Korea can't control people. " He's not that afraid of viruses, but he's afraid of living with them. South Korea is not forced to stop or shut down, the outbreak of almost all rely on the self-protection of residents. However, this "all-on-your-own" approach has rattled Xiaoxue.

Xiaoxue studied in Taegu and took a part-time job at a hotpot restaurant after school ended in December. She plans to go home again in February, in South Korea to study for Korean level 5 and save some living expenses for the next semester. However, Xiaoxue cancelled his plans to return home because of the outbreak at home. When her parents in Weihai began calling her every day to remind her to be safe, Xiaoxue had not expected the new pneumonia to become a global epidemic.

After the super spreader, Xiaoxue received almost daily alerts from the Taegu government. Her part-time hot pot restaurant has seen a marked decrease in the flow of customers, but there are also bold guests, "do not wear a mask also dinner together. ". Despite the drop in business, the boss was reluctant to close, "the worst of the few days only had to close for four days. ". In addition to purchasing disinfectant water and face masks, the hotpot shop did not specifically propose sanitary measures to deal with the epidemic, which made Xiaoxue a little nervous. "It feels like the epidemic prevention here is entirely self-conscious. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taegu Street during the epidemic. Photograph: Xiaoxue

When not working, Xiaoxue would study in a rented room. For the first time since the outbreak, the South Korean government has delayed the start of classes, which may be replaced with online courses. But Xiaoxue says there is no difference between offline and online classes because she doesn't speak Korean well enough to understand the lessons.

Most schools are cutting back on hours because of delayed start times and online instruction. On March 2, some netizens launched a petition to reduce or waive tuition fees for the first semester of 2020. If more than 100,000 people take part in the petition on April 1, Blue House may respond. On March 4, Xiaoxue also clicked "yes" on the petition link, which had already attracted nearly 50,000 people.

More than a third of the students in the outbreak are in self-imposed quarantine in South Korea, and some are considering returning home or have already done so, according to the struggle in Korea Forum. Xiao Han is one of the students preparing to return home, less than a month after her last trip back to school.

On February 10, the Keimyung University sent an email to Chinese students, informing them that all students must return to South Korea between February 21 and 24 or face an automatic suspension. Because do not want to drop out of school, Little Han immediately bought a good return ticket ready to go back to school.

At 11:50 am on February 24, he flew from Weihai to Seoul and landed at Incheon Airport at 2 pm. She was asked to download a self diagnostic APP at a makeshift site set up at the airport and was asked to keep daily records of her condition for the next 14 days. But Small Han thinks"this software registers a body condition to be able to cheat completely, made and did not make same".

That day at 3:00 pm, Xiaohan left Incheon Airport and took a bus to Dongdaqiu. On the car found that the driver and as usual did not wear a mask, four and a half hours to make small Han feel particularly long. When they arrived in Dongdaegu, there were buses to take them to school. "there were only four students on the big buses. ". Xiao Han school dormitory door set up a temporary epidemic prevention station, health care doctors and nurses will do a simple inspection and epidemic prevention. Arriving students will be quarantined in their dormitories for two weeks, during which the International Cooperation Center will provide daily necessities and food.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Lunch in quarantine. Photograph: Xiao Han

He had expected school to start after the quarantine ended, but the outbreak in Taegu took place at an unexpected rate. Her parents were worried about her safety and wanted her to return home. Because she was quarantined on returning to school, she failed to pay her tuition by the February deadline, and her application must be submitted between March 23 and 27, according to school rules. With all flights in Taegu suspended, he didn't have much time to wait and see, so he bought a ticket for the March 11 departure from Seoul, "you can apply for a suspension online, go back first. ".

Because originally planned to leave South Korea on March 11, after the end of the quarantine, small Han stayed at a friend's house. On the afternoon of March 7th, however, a message on his mobile phone warned him that his flight home had been cancelled. She immediately compared the fare, and the price went up from the date. "He couldn't afford it, " he said, snatching a flight from Incheon airport to Weihai at 10:30 the next morning.

Half an hour later, the tickets came out. Xiao Han hurriedly packed his luggage, ready to go to the Incheon airport overnight. Some students choose to hire a car directly, some small Han reluctant to part with 350,000 won (about 2,100 yuan) in the charter fee, in that there is a bus, small Han took a taxi to Dongdaegu, ready to take a bus from Dongdaqiu to Incheon airport.

On the way to the East Daegu, "not properly wear a mask" taxi driver let Xiaohan some fear, the driver even took off the mask and her talk and hand high-five with her, scared Xiaohan "can only give themselves more disinfection.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xiaohan is waiting in the Waiting Hall of Dongdaqiu station for the bus to Incheon Airport. Photographer: Han

At 12:30 pm, Xiao Han's bus leaves from Dongdaegu to Incheon Airport. Two seats away from her is a Chinese woman, "wearing gloves, wearing protective clothing fully armed. ". More people on the bus than expected, basically are Chinese, met compatriots and people around enough protection to let small Han's heart a little bit settled down.

As dawn approaches, he arrives at Incheon Airport, which is much larger than the "at a glance" Taegu airport. Xiaohan took the subway to his boarding gate, together with the basic waiting for the plane are compatriots, everyone neatly wearing a mask.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
People waiting at Incheon airport. Photograph: Xiao Han

At 10:30 a.m. on March 8, he landed at Weihai airport after an hour-long flight and an hour-long time difference. After the plane stops and is checked by the epidemic prevention personnel, all the passengers will be seated in the hall in batches according to their gender and seat number. They will take body temperature and fill in relevant forms to record their physical condition and personal information. Because it was women's Day, the airport's epidemic prevention officers also sent flowers to the female passengers.

At first he thought there would be extra checks on passengers from Taegu, but all passengers at Weihai airport were checked the same way: Take your temperature, fill out a form -- Foshan -- almost the same, and fill it out six times. Little Han is ready to be strictly examined and cross-examined, but the airport inspectors, heavily armed, do not seem to care about the word "Daegu" . After taking his temperature and filling out the form, he and all the other passengers were divided by the area where they lived. They took different buses and were driven by police cars to the corresponding isolation points.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Delta has added a special layer of film between the CAB and the car. Photographer: Han

From the time he left school on March 7 until he reached the quarantine point, he did not eat or drink. She thought she would be able to go home after seven or seven days in isolation, like her classmates before her, but was told she would need 14 days. When her mother found out about it, she rode the mule to see her. Because this side of the road in the Isolation Hotel Road Repair, small Han and across the street in the mother only looked at a distance.

The isolated hotel environment where Xiaohan is located. Photograph: Xiaohan

And Xiaohan the same batch, check into the same quarantine hotel, a total of nine people. Across the wall, Little Han heard someone say that the air conditioning was not heating. She turned on the air conditioner in her room, which was warm only when she stood directly below it. The cookies and instant noodles sent by the staff made her miss the three meals she ate during the Korean quarantine. She was so hungry that she hoped the dinner would improve. As of Feb. 25, more than 350 of the more than 1,000 Chinese students studying abroad at the Keimyung University had chosen to drop out, a growing number, according to an administrative notice from the Keimyung University.

Originally, small Han want to take advantage of the holidays in South Korea part-time, for the next semester to earn a little tuition. Even with a 50% fee reduction, han still thinks a semester is a bit expensive, and the two trips are worth a month's salary.

This is the first time Han suspended school, but also the first time she left home only half a month to return the same way. Her isolation point is just three minutes from home, but it will be at least 14 days before she can return home.

The Old Cao, ah Bai, Xiaoxue and Xiao Han are all pseudonyms.
